\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Book Twenty One\uc0\u8232 Achilles Fights the River\
[Achilles attacks the Trojans hiding in the river Xanthus (also called Scamander); takes twelve young men alive to sacrifice for Patroclus; Achilles meets Lycaon, who begs for mercy; Achilles replies and then kills Lycaon; Achilles fights and kills Asteropaeus, then slaughters many Paeonian leaders; the river objects to the slaughter; the river rises against Achilles, who appeals to the gods for help; Hera appeals to Hephaestus to fight the river; Hephaestus launches his fire against the flooding river; the river gives up, so Hephaestus withdraws his fire; the gods begin to fight each other; Athena fights Ares and then Aphrodite; Poseidon offers to fight Apollo, who declines; Hera and Artemis fight; Apollo moves into Ilion; Apollo deceives Achilles, enabling many Trojans to reach the city]\
When the Trojans reached the ford across the Xanthus,\uc0\u8232 lovely swirling river born of immortal Zeus,\u8232 Achilles split them in two groups, chasing one\u8232 across the plain towards the city, where the previous day\u8232 Achaeans had fled in terror, when glorious Hector\u8232 had prevailed. Some Trojans fled back there in panic.\u8232 Hera sent fog in front of them to slow them down.\u8232 But half the Trojans were crammed in along the river,\u8232 trapped by its deep currents and its silver eddies.\u8232 They fell in there, making a huge commotion.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a010\u8232 The noise roared down along the rushing river banks\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[10]\u8232 amplifying the din. Men thrashed around, back and forth,\u8232 as they were sucked down in the current screaming.\u8232 Just as fire drives flights of locusts to seek refuge\u8232 in some river, when the tireless flames attack them\u8232 in a sudden onrush and they sink below the water\'97\u8232 that\'92s how, faced with Achilles\'92 attacking charge,\u8232 a confused mass of chariots and men filled up\u8232 the deep and swirling waters of the river Xanthus.\
Then divinely born Achilles left his spear\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a020\uc0\u8232 beside a tamarisk bush and jumped into the stream,\u8232 like an inhuman thing, armed only with his sword,\u8232 his heart intent on killing. Turning in all directions,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[20]\u8232 he kept on striking. The men his sword slaughtered\u8232 cried out in terror. The water turned blood red.\u8232 Just as other fish swim off from a huge dolphin\u8232 filling safe corners of some sheltered harbour,\u8232 fearful because the beast eats all it captures\'97\u8232 that\'92s how Trojans huddled then, under hanging banks,\u8232 all along the stream edge of that murderous river.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a030\u8232 When Achilles\'92 arms grew weary from the killing,\u8232 he plucked out of the river twelve young men alive,\u8232 as blood payment for the killing of Patroclus,\u8232 Menoetius\'92 son. He led them up onto dry land,\u8232 like stupefied fawns, tied their hands behind them,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\u8232 using belts they wore around their woven tunics,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[30]\u8232 and gave them to his men to lead back to the ships.\u8232 Then he jumped in again, eager to keep killing.\
But then Achilles met someone fleeing the river\'97\uc0\u8232 Lycaon, a son of Dardanian Priam,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a040\u8232 whom he\'92d captured once before in a night attack,\u8232 taking him against his will from his father\'92s orchard.\u8232 With his sharp bronze Lycaon had been cutting\u8232 young shoots from off a fig tree to make chariot rails.\u8232 He\'92d had the bad luck to meet godlike Achilles.\u8232 That time, Achilles took him in his ship and sold him\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[40]\u8232 in well-built Lemnos, where the son of Jason\u8232 had paid the purchase price. From there, E\'ebtion,\u8232 a friend and guest from Imbros, had ransomed Lycaon,\u8232 paying a huge sum, then sent him on to Arisbe.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a050\u8232 He\'92d escaped from there in secret and gone home,\u8232 back to his father\'92s house. Once he returned from Lemnos,\u8232 for eleven days his heart enjoyed his friends.\u8232 On the twelfth, some god threw him back again\u8232 into Achilles\'92 hands, who was about to ship him,\u8232 against Lycaon\'92s wishes, down to dwell with Hades.\u8232 When swift-footed, godlike Achilles saw Lycaon\u8232 totally unarmed, without his helmet, shield, or spear,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[50]\u8232 for he\'92d thrown these on the ground, exhausted\u8232 after he\'92d escaped the river, worn out and sweating\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a060\u8232 in all his lower limbs, Achilles, much surprised,\u8232 spoke to his own courageous heart:\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'93What\'92s this?\uc0\u8232 My eyes are witnessing something amazing.\u8232 Great-hearted Trojans I\'92ve just slaughtered\u8232 will rise again, up out of murky darkness,\u8232 if this man\'92s avoided death, returned like this,\u8232 after I\'92d sold him off in sacred Lemnos.\u8232 The grey sea, which holds many people back\u8232 against their will, hasn\'92t seemed to stop him.\u8232 But come, let him taste my spear point. I\'92ll see\'97\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a070\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[60]\u8232 and in my heart confirm\'97if he\'92ll return,\u8232 as he\'92s just done, or if life-giving earth,\u8232 which keeps even strong men down, will hold him.\'94\
That\'92s what Achilles thought, as he stood there waiting.\uc0\u8232 Lycaon, dazed with fear, approached Achilles,\u8232 eager to clasp his knees in supplication,\u8232 heart desperate to escape dark fate and evil death.\u8232 Godlike Achilles raised his long spear, prepared to strike.\u8232 But Lycaon, stooping down, slipped underneath the spear,\u8232 then clasped Achilles\'92 knees. Flying above his back,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a080\u8232 the spear stuck in the ground, hungry for human flesh.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[70]\u8232 With one hand, Lycaon grabbed Achilles\'92 knee.\u8232 His other clutched the spear, refusing to let go.\u8232 He begged for mercy, addressing Achilles\u8232 with these winged words:\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'93By your knees, Achilles,\uc0\u8232 I beg you to respect me as a suppliant.\u8232 Have pity on me. I claim that sacred right,\u8232 my lord, because it was at your table\u8232 I first ate Demeter\'92s grain the very day\u8232 you seized me in that well-built orchard.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a090\u8232 You led me far from father and my friends,\u8232 then sold me off in sacred Lemnos. For me\u8232 you got the value of a hundred oxen,\u8232 but I was ransomed for three times that price.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[80]\u8232 It\'92s now twelve days since I reached Ilion,\u8232 after my ordeal. Once more, deadly Fate\u8232 has placed me in your hands. I do believe\u8232 Father Zeus must hate me, to give me to you\u8232 for a second time. My mother, Laotho\'eb,\u8232 daughter of old Altes, gave birth to me\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0100\u8232 to live a shortened life. Altes rules over\u8232 war-loving Leleges, in steep Pedasus,\u8232 by the river Satnioeis. His daughter\u8232 married Priam, who has many other wives.\u8232 She had two sons. Now you\'92ll have slaughtered both.\u8232 You killed fine Polydorus with those men\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[90]\u8232 fighting at the front, when your sharp spear\u8232 sent him to die. Now death comes for me, as well.\u8232 I don\'92t expect to escape your hands this time,\u8232 since some god has guided me right to them.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0110\u8232 But I\'92ll say one more thing\'97take it to heart\'97\u8232 don\'92t kill me. I\'92m not from the same womb\u8232 as Hector, the man who killed your comrade,\u8232 that kind and powerful warrior.\'94\
So Lycaon begged for mercy from Achilles.\uc0\u8232 But the response he got was brutal:\
\'a0 \'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'93You fool,\uc0\u8232 don\'92t offer me a ransom or some plea.\u8232 Before Patroclus met his deadly fate,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[100]\u8232 sparing Trojans pleased my heart much more.\u8232 I took many overseas and sold them.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0120\u8232 But now not one of them escapes his death,\u8232 no one whom god delivers to my hands,\u8232 here in front of Ilion, not one\'97\u8232 not a single Trojan, especially none\u8232 of Priam\'92s children. So now, my friend,\u8232 you too must die. Why be sad about it?\u8232 Patroclus died, a better man than you.\u8232 And look at me. You see how fine I am,\u8232 how tall, how handsome? My father\'92s a fine man,\u8232 the mother who gave birth to me a goddess.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0130\u8232 Yet over me, as well, hangs Fate\'97my death.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[110]\u8232 There\'92ll come a dawn, or noon, or evening,\u8232 when some man will take my life in battle\'97\u8232 he\'92ll strike me with his spear or with an arrow\u8232 shot from his bowstring.\'94\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0Achilles finished.\uc0\u8232 Then Lycaon\'92s knees gave way, his heart collapsed.\u8232 He let go of the spear and crouched there, both his hands\u8232 stretched out. Achilles pulled out his sharp sword and struck,\u8232 hitting him on the collar bone, beside his neck.\u8232 The whole two-edged blade sliced into him. Lycaon fell,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0140\u8232 lying face down on the earth. His dark blood flowed out\u8232 and soaked the ground. Achilles seized him by the foot,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[120]\u8232 then flung him in the river, shouting out in triumph\'97\u8232 his words had wings:\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'93Lie there, among the fish.\uc0\u8232 They\'92ll lick blood from your wound with no respect.\u8232 Your mother won\'92t set you on your funeral bed,\u8232 lamenting over you. No, Scamander,\u8232 the swirling river, will carry you away\u8232 to the broad lap of the sea. Many fish\u8232 will swim up to the darkly rippled surface\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0150\u8232 to eat white fat from Lycaon. So die,\u8232 all you fleeing Trojans, until we reach\u8232 that sacred city Ilion, with me there,\u8232 right behind you, fighting and killing you.\u8232 Your flowing river with its silver eddies\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[130]\u8232 won\'92t help, for all those bulls you\'92ve sacrificed\u8232 all these years, all the sure-footed horses\u8232 you\'92ve thrown alive into its swirling pools.\u8232 No matter\'97you\'92ll suffer an evil fate,\u8232 till every one of you has paid in full\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0160\u8232 for Patroclus\'92 death, for Achaea\'92s dead,\u8232 the men you slaughtered by our swift ships,\u8232 when I was not among them there.\'94\
Achilles\'92 words enraged the heart in river Xanthus,\uc0\u8232 who wondered how he might stop godlike Achilles\u8232 from his slaughter and protect the Trojans from disaster.\u8232 Meanwhile, Peleus\'92 son, gripping his long-shadowed spear,\u8232 still eager to kill more, charged Asteropaeus,\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[140]\u8232 son of Pelegon, born to the broad river Axius\u8232 and Acessamenus\'92 eldest daughter, Periboea.\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0170\u8232 The deep swirling river had had sex with her.\u8232 Achilles went at Asteropaeus, who stood there,\u8232 facing him, holding two spears. In his anger\u8232 at the slaughter of young soldiers in the battle,\u8232 whom Achilles kept butchering along the stream,\u8232 showing no pity, Xanthus then put fighting strength\u8232 into Asteropaeus. But when the two men\u8232 had approached each other, moving close together,\u8232 godlike Achilles was the first to speak:\
\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'93Who are you that dares to come against me?\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0180\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0\'a0[150]\uc0\u8232 Where are you from? Children who confront me\u8232 leave their parents full of sorrow.\'94\
The glorious son of Pelegon then said in reply:\
